    "isClassic": true,
    "originalAuthor": "Kenneth Grahame",
    "description": "Mr. Toad's motor-car obsession leads his friends on a wild adventure.",
    "duration": "10",
    "pages": [
      [
        "Page 1",
        "Deep in the English countryside stood Toad Hall, the grandest house by the river. It belonged to Mr. Toad — plump, jolly, and famous for his fads. One week it was boating. The next, ballooning. Each hobby lasted until the next shiny idea came along. His friends Ratty, Mole, and Badger shook their heads. 'Dear Toad,' sighed the Water Rat. 'Always off chasing something new.'"
      ],
      [
        "Page 2",
        "One bright morning, Toad came bounding down the path. 'A caravan!' he cried. 'The open road, dear fellows! Fresh air, adventure!' Rat grumbled, but Mole was tickled, and soon the three of them were trundling along with a canary-yellow cart. Hedges bloomed. Bees hummed. Toad sang tunelessly from the driver's seat. For one whole afternoon, he was perfectly, completely happy."
      ],
      [
        "Page 3",
        "Then it happened. A cloud of dust. A terrible honk. A great motor-car roared past in a blur of brass and thunder, flinging the caravan into a ditch. Rat shook his fist. Mole trembled. But Toad sat in the road, eyes shining, whispering, 'Poop-poop!' He had forgotten the caravan. He had forgotten his friends. His heart belonged now to the motor-car."
      ],
      [
        "Page 4",
        "From that day, Toad was lost to motor-mania. He bought one car, then another, and another still. Each one he drove too fast, until — crash! — into a hedge, a wall, or a pond. Seven motor-cars he smashed. Seven times the doctor came. Seven times the policemen frowned. And every time Toad sat up in bed and cried, 'Poop-poop! Wasn't it splendid?'"
      ],
      [
        "Page 5",
        "Word of Toad's wild ways spread all down the riverbank. Mole wrung his paws. Rat paced by the water. 'He'll come to real harm,' Rat said. 'Or worse — lose Toad Hall itself.' The animals of the Wild Wood whispered together, eyeing the grand house with hungry looks. Something had to be done, and quickly. But who was brave enough to stop a Toad in full flight?"
      ],
      [
        "Page 6",
        "Badger was. Striped, stout, and wise as winter, Badger seldom stirred from his burrow. But when he did stir, animals listened. 'Tomorrow,' he rumbled one frosty morning, 'we go to Toad Hall. We will take him in hand, for his own good.' Rat nodded firmly. Mole squared his small shoulders. Together, the three friends set out at dawn, determined and grave."
      ],
      [
        "Page 7",
        "Toad greeted them in an enormous driving-coat, goggles pushed up on his head. 'Dear friends! Just in time — I'm off for a spin!' 'Oh no you're not,' said Badger quietly, and shut the front door behind them. Toad blinked. He tried to bluster. He tried to laugh. But Badger's steady eye was fixed upon him, and Toad's bluster crumbled like dry leaves."
      ],
      [
        "Page 8",
        "Badger led Toad into the smoking-room and spoke to him long and seriously. Out came Toad, snuffling into a handkerchief. 'I am a wicked, foolish toad,' he sobbed. 'I renounce motor-cars forever!' But the moment his friends' backs were turned, Toad's tears dried. A sly smile crept across his face. 'Renounce motor-cars?' he whispered. 'Not for all the world!'"
      ],
      [
        "Page 9",
        "So the friends locked Toad's bedroom door and took turns guarding it. Days passed. Toad refused his meals. He groaned dreadfully. 'Oh, I am so ill,' he moaned to Ratty. 'Fetch the doctor — quickly!' Ratty, kind-hearted soul, hurried off at once. The door clicked shut. Toad sprang from the bed, nimble as a cricket, and rubbed his hands. His plan was working."
      ],
      [
        "Page 10",
        "Toad knotted the bedsheets into a rope and slipped through the window. Down he went, past the ivy, past the roses, thump onto the lawn. He scampered across the fields like a schoolboy on holiday, whistling loudly. 'Ho, ho!' he chuckled. 'Poor old Badger! Poor old Rat! How clever I am, and how splendid life is — especially for a toad named Toad!'"
      ],
      [
        "Page 11",
        "By afternoon, footsore and hungry, Toad wandered into a cheerful little inn called The Red Lion. He ordered luncheon and sat down by the window. Then he saw it. Parked in the yard, gleaming in the sun, sat a magnificent motor-car. Its owners were inside, eating pie. Toad's eyes went round. His fingers twitched. 'Poop-poop,' he breathed softly. 'Oh dear. Oh dear, oh dear.'"
      ],
      [
        "Page 12",
        "Toad tiptoed out. He slid behind the wheel. The engine purred. Something wild woke inside him, and away he flew, down lanes and over bridges, faster and faster. The hedges blurred. The wind whipped his coat. He was Toad the Terror, Toad the Magnificent, Toad who laughed at rules! 'Poop-poop!' he shouted to the sky. 'Nothing can catch me now!'"
      ],
      [
        "Page 13",
        "But something could. A policeman's whistle shrilled. Toad swerved, the car wobbled, and — splash! — it sailed clean into a duck-pond. Toad climbed out, dripping weeds, just as two constables came pounding down the road. 'Stop, thief!' they cried. Toad, who had never run so fast in his life, took to his heels and dashed wildly into the dark woods beyond."
      ],
      [
        "Page 14",
        "For hours Toad stumbled on, cold and miserable. The grand coat was ruined. The goggles were lost. 'Oh, I am a foolish toad,' he wept, sitting on a log. 'How right Badger was!' He thought of Toad Hall, warm and bright. He thought of dear Ratty's fire. And for the first time in a long while, Mr. Toad felt truly, properly sorry."
      ],
      [
        "Page 15",
        "At last, moonlight glimmered on a familiar river. Toad tapped on Rat's little door. Rat flung it open and gasped. 'Toady! You scamp! You scallywag!' But he bundled Toad inside and set hot toast before him. Then Rat's face grew serious. 'I have grim news, old friend. While you were gallivanting, the weasels of the Wild Wood crept in and took Toad Hall.'"
      ],
      [
        "Page 16",
        "Toad's jaw dropped. Toad Hall, his beautiful home, in the paws of weasels! Badger and Mole arrived that very evening, wise faces grave. 'Not to worry,' said Badger, tapping the table. 'I know a secret. There's a tunnel, an old, forgotten passage, that leads right into Toad Hall's pantry. Tomorrow night, the weasels are throwing a great feast. That shall be our moment.'"
      ],
      [
        "Page 17",
        "The next night, armed with stout sticks and brave hearts, the four friends crept through the tunnel. Up they popped into the pantry, right beside the banquet hall. With a tremendous shout they burst in — Badger booming, Rat darting, Mole whooping, Toad hopping! The weasels, taken by surprise, squealed and scattered in every direction. In ten minutes, Toad Hall belonged to Toad once more."
      ],
      [
        "Page 18",
        "They held a splendid supper to celebrate. Toad stood to make a speech — a long, boastful one, he planned — but caught Badger's steady eye. He coughed. He sat down. 'Thank you, dear friends,' he said simply. 'I have been a silly toad. I mean to be better.' And outside, the river murmured its approval, and the willows whispered, welcome home."
      ]
    ],
